\pard\li360\sb240\sa240\sl23\slmult0 Implement the PageRank algorithm to rank web pages based on link analysis.\par
Apply the PageRank algorithm to a small web graph and analyze the results.\par

\pard\sb240\sa240\sl23\slmult0\b Theory:\par

\pard\li360\sb240\sa240\sl23\slmult0\b0\fs28 Link analysis refers to the examination of hyperlinks between web pages to evaluate their relationships and significance.\par
PageRank assigns a numerical score to each page, representing its importance.\par
\b\f1 input:\par
\b0 import numpy as np\par
 \par
def page_rank(graph, damping_factor=0.85, max_iterations=100, tolerance=1e-6):\par
    # Get the number of nodes\par
    num_nodes = len(graph)\par
 \par
    # Initialize PageRank Values\par
    page_rank = np.ones(num_nodes) / num_nodes\par
 \par
    # Iterative PageRank Calculation\par
    for _ in range(max_iterations):\par
        prev_page_ranks = np.copy(page_rank)\par
 \par
        for node in range(num_nodes):\par
            # Calculate the contribution from incoming links\par
            incoming_links = [i for i, neighbors in enumerate(graph) if node in neighbors]  \par
            if not incoming_links:\par
                continue\par
            page_rank[node] = (1 - damping_factor) / num_nodes + damping_factor * sum(prev_page_ranks[link] / len(graph[link]) if len(graph[link]) else 0 for link in incoming_links)\par
       \par
        # Check for convergence\par
        if np.linalg.norm(page_rank - prev_page_ranks, 2) < tolerance:\par
            break\par
 \par
    return page_rank\par
 \par
# Example usage\par
# Changed _name_ to __name__ to use the correct special variable\par
if __name__ == "__main__":\par
    web_graph = [[1, 2], [0, 2], [0, 1], [1, 2]]\par
 \par
    # Calculate PageRank\par
    result = page_rank(web_graph)\par
    for i, pr in enumerate(result):\par
        print(f"Page \{i\}: \{pr\}")\par
